    {
        "content": "<p>Another perhaps weirder answer to your question is to ask another question: <em>why</em> do you want such a theorem? Often mathematicians claim to want this theorem because they like seeing things in some kind of canonical form, but sometimes this is just psychological. If there's an induction principle for FreeGroup of the form \"if P is a property of elements, if P(1) is true, if P(a_i) and P(a_i^{-1}) are true for all i, and if P(x) and P(y) implies P(xy), then P(g) is true for all g in the group\" then you don't need the theorem which you are asking for.</p>",
        "id": 490343325,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1734827414
    }
]